Briefly discuss the stages of shock ( 5 mks )
There are three stages:
1. Nonprogressive stage/compensated stage.
2. Progressive stage
3. Irreversible stage

Nonprogressive stage/compensated stage
In the initial stage of shock the body experiences a reduced cardiac output.
The cells switches from aerobic to anaerobic respiration.
The sympathetic reflexes and other factors compensate enough to prevent further deterioration.

The factors causing recovery are all negative feedback control mechanisms of circulation that attempt to return cardiac output and arterial pressure back to normal.

In this stage the body has lost compensatory mechanisms which have maintained tissue perfusion up to this time. This decrease in perfusion results in metabolic acidosis,electrolyte imbalance.

Some positive feedback mechanisms further depress cardiac output in shock, thus causing shock to become progressive.

They include:
-cardiac depression
-vasomotor failure
-blockage of very small vessels-sludged blood
-increased capillary permeability
-release of toxins by ischaemic tissue
-cardiac depression caused by endotoxin
-generalised cellular deterioration
-tissue necrosis in severe shock.

Irreversible shock
This is whereby shock has progressed to a certain stage that transfusion or any other therapy becomes incapable of saving the persons life.

